  "prompt": "Can I use any image from google/website in my blog, along with mentioning the credits for the image?",
  "response": "Using images from Google or any website in your blog requires careful attention to copyright laws. Here are some guidelines:\n\n1. **Public Domain or Creative Commons:** Look for images that are explicitly labeled as public domain or available under a Creative Commons license. Make sure you comply with the terms of the license, including proper attribution and any usage restrictions.\n\n2. **Royalty-Free Images:** Many websites offer royalty-free images that can be used in your blog, either for free or for a fee. Examples include Unsplash, Pixabay, and Pexels. Check the usage terms for each image to ensure compliance.\n\n3. **Original Content:** Create your own images or use images that you have personally purchased or licensed.\n\n4. **Permission:** If you want to use an image that is not clearly licensed for public use or Creative Commons, contact the owner or creator for permission to use the image.\n\n5. **Fair Use:** In some cases, you may be able to use images under the doctrine of fair use, which allows limited use of copyrighted material without permission. Fair use typically includes commentary, criticism, news reporting, teaching, and research. However, this is a complicated area of law and not always clear-cut.\n\nSimply crediting the image's source does not automatically make it legally permissible to use. The safest approach is to use images that you have clear permission to use under the relevant terms or those that are explicitly free to use.",
